Estimating Static Games

Data

  • Required libraries
easypackages::libraries(c('tidyverse', 'EmpiricalIO2020'))
  • Load the data and name the columns.
df <- read_csv('../input/data/GIO2020PS21Data.csv', col_names = FALSE) %>% 
  magrittr::set_colnames(c('entry_1', 'entry_2', 'entry_sum', 'population', 'dist_1', 'dist_2'))

First Step

  • In this step, we construct the choice probability, \[ \hat{\sigma_i}(a_i \mid \textit{pop}_m, \textit{dist}_{1m}, \textit{dist}_{1m}) \] by logit model with 3rd order polynomials.
logit_1 <- df %>% 
  select(entry_1, population, dist_1, dist_2) %>% 
  glm(entry_1 ~ poly(population, dist_1, dist_2, degree = 3, raw = TRUE), family = 'binomial', data = .)

logit_2 <- df %>% 
  select(entry_2, population, dist_1, dist_2) %>% 
  glm(entry_2 ~ poly(population, dist_1, dist_2, degree = 3, raw = TRUE), family = 'binomial', data = .)

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(prob_entry_1 = predict(logit_1, ., type = 'response'),
           prob_entry_2 = predict(logit_2, ., type = 'response'))
df

Second Step

  • The log-likelihood is \[ \ln L(\alpha,\beta,\delta) = \sum_{m=1}^{M}\sum_{i=1}^{2}(a_{im} \ln \text{Pr}(a_{im}=1\mid\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\hat{\sigma}_{-i})+(1-a_{im})(1- \ln\text{Pr}(a_{im}=0\mid\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\hat{\sigma}_{-i})). \]
# initial theta
theta <- c(1, -1, -1)


# optimization
optim_result <- optim(theta, HW4_lkhd, df = df, method = 'Nelder-Mead', control = list(fnscale = -1))
optim_result

Bootstrap

  • Let us calculate the standar error by boot strap.
  • We use parallel computation to make it fast.
# register
library(doParallel)
cl <- parallel::makePSOCKcluster(4)
doParallel::registerDoParallel(cl)

# set.seed
set.seed(1)

result = foreach (i = 1:1000,
               .packages = c('dplyr', 'purrr', 'NumbersGame'),
               .combine = 'rbind') %dopar% 
              {
                 # bootstrap sample  
                 df_bs <- sample_n(df, NROW(df), replace = TRUE)
                 theta <-  c(1, -1, -1)
                 optim(theta, EmpiricalIO2020::HW4_lkhd, df = df_bs, method = 'Nelder-Mead', control = list(fnscale = -1))$par
              }

# kill finished tasks
parallel::stopCluster(cl)

# se
cat(paste0('se of alpha is ', round(sd(result[,1]), 3)))
se of alpha is 0.033
cat(paste0('se of alpha is ', round(sd(result[,2]), 3)))
se of alpha is 0.049
cat(paste0('se of alpha is ', round(sd(result[,3]), 3)))
se of alpha is 0.093

  • In sum, we obtained the following result (s.e. in the parenthesis): \[ \hat{\alpha} = 0.52 (0.033), \hat{\beta} = -0.69 (0.049),\hat{\delta } = -0.36 (0.093). \]

  • The sign of the estimates are consistent with intuition.
